 020:     """The famous *SVD* algorithm, as popularized by `Simon Funk
 021:     <http://sifter.org/~simon/journal/20061211.html>`_ during the Netflix
 022:     Prize. When baselines are not used, this is equivalent to Probabilistic
 023:     Matrix Factorization :cite:`salakhutdinov2008a` (see :ref:`note
 024:     <unbiased_note>` below).
 025: 
 026:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 027: 
 028:     .. math::
 029:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u
 030: 
 031:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 032:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 033:     with :math:`b_i` and :math:`q_i`.
 034: 
 035:     For details, see equation (5) from :cite:`Koren:2009`. See also
 036:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 037: 
 038:     To estimate all the unknown, we minimize the following regularized squared
 039:     error:
 040: 
 041:     .. math::
 042:         \sum_{r_{ui} \in R_{train}} \left(r_{ui} - \hat{r}_{ui} \\right)^2 +
 043:         \lambda\\left(b_i^2 + b_u^2 + ||q_i||^2 + ||p_u||^2\\right)
 044: 
 045: 
 046:     The minimization is performed by a very straightforward stochastic gradient
 047:     descent:
 048: 
 049:     .. math::
 050:         b_u &\\leftarrow b_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_u)\\\\
 051:         b_i &\\leftarrow b_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} - \lambda b_i)\\\\
 052:         p_u &\\leftarrow p_u &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot q_i - \lambda p_u)\\\\
 053:         q_i &\\leftarrow q_i &+ \gamma (e_{ui} \\cdot p_u - \lambda q_i)
 054: 
 055:     where :math:`e_{ui} = r_{ui} - \\hat{r}_{ui}`. These steps are performed
 056:     over all the ratings of the trainset and repeated ``n_epochs`` times.
 057:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 058:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 059:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 060: 
 061:     You also have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 062:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 063:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 064:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 065: 
 066:     .. _unbiased_note:
 067: 
 068:     .. note::
 069:         You can choose to use an unbiased version of this algorithm, simply
 070:         predicting:
 071: 
 072:         .. math::
 073:             \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u
 074: 
 075:         This is equivalent to Probabilistic Matrix Factorization
 076:         (:cite:`salakhutdinov2008a`, section 2) and can be achieved by setting
 077:         the ``biased`` parameter to ``False``.
 078: 
 079: 
 080:     Args:
 081:         # 隐变量的维度数
 082:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``100``.
 083:         # SGD(其实这里是BGD)迭代多少轮
 084:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 085:             ``20``.
 086:         # 数据是否是有偏的
 087:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). See :ref:`note
 088:             <unbiased_note>` above.  Default is ``True``.
 089:         # factor ：正态分布均值
 090:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 091:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 092:         # factor ： 正态分布方差
 093:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 094:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 095:         # 学习速率
 096:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.005``.
 097:         # 正则化项
 098:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 099:             ``0.02``.
 100:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 101:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 102:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 103:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 104:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 105:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 106:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 107:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 108:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 109:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 110:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 111:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 112:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 113:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 114:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 115:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 116:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 117:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 118:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 119:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 120:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 121:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 122:             ``None``.
 123:         # 是否可视化执行过程
 124:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 125: 
 126:     Attributes:
 127:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 128:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 129:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 130:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 131:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 132:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 133:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 134:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)

 170:         # OK, let's breath. I've seen so many different implementation of this
 171:         # algorithm that I just not sure anymore of what it should do. I've
 172:         # implemented the version as described in the BellKor papers (RS
 173:         # Handbook, etc.). Mymedialite also does it this way. In his post
 174:         # however, Funk seems to implicitly say that the algo looks like this
 175:         # (see reg below):
 176:         # for f in range(n_factors):
 177:         #       for _ in range(n_iter):
 178:         #           for u, i, r in all_ratings:
 179:         #               err = r_ui - <p[u, :f+1], q[i, :f+1]>
 180:         #               update p[u, f]
 181:         #               update q[i, f]
 182:         # which is also the way https://github.com/aaw/IncrementalSVD.jl
 183:         # implemented it.
 184:         #
 185:         # Funk: "Anyway, this will train one feature (aspect), and in
 186:         # particular will find the most prominent feature remaining (the one
 187:         # that will most reduce the error that's left over after previously
 188:         # trained features have done their best). When it's as good as it's
 189:         # going to get, shift it onto the pile of done features, and start a
 190:         # new one. For efficiency's sake, cache the residuals (all 100 million
 191:         # of them) so when you're training feature 72 you don't have to wait
 192:         # for predictRating() to re-compute the contributions of the previous
 193:         # 71 features. You will need 2 Gig of ram, a C compiler, and good
 194:         # programming habits to do this."

 298:     """The *SVD++* algorithm, an extension of :class:`SVD` taking into account
 299:     implicit ratings.
 300: 
 301:     The prediction :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 302: 
 303:     .. math::
 304:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^T\\left(p_u +
 305:         |I_u|^{-\\frac{1}{2}} \sum_{j \\in I_u}y_j\\right)
 306: 
 307:     Where the :math:`y_j` terms are a new set of item factors that capture
 308:     implicit ratings. Here, an implicit rating describes the fact that a user
 309:     :math:`u` rated an item :math:`j`, regardless of the rating value.
 310: 
 311:     If user :math:`u` is unknown, then the bias :math:`b_u` and the factors
 312:     :math:`p_u` are assumed to be zero. The same applies for item :math:`i`
 313:     with :math:`b_i`, :math:`q_i` and :math:`y_i`.
 314: 
 315: 
 316:     For details, see section 4 of :cite:`Koren:2008:FMN`. See also
 317:     :cite:`Ricci:2010`, section 5.3.1.
 318: 
 319:     Just as for :class:`SVD`, the parameters are learned using a SGD on the
 320:     regularized squared error objective.
 321: 
 322:     Baselines are initialized to ``0``. User and item factors are randomly
 323:     initialized according to a normal distribution, which can be tuned using
 324:     the ``init_mean`` and ``init_std_dev`` parameters.
 325: 
 326:     You have control over the learning rate :math:`\gamma` and the
 327:     regularization term :math:`\lambda`. Both can be different for each
 328:     kind of parameter (see below). By default, learning rates are set to
 329:     ``0.005`` and regularization terms are set to ``0.02``.
 330: 
 331:     Args:
 332:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``20``.
 333:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 334:             ``20``.
 335:         init_mean: The mean of the normal distribution for factor vectors
 336:             initialization. Default is ``0``.
 337:         init_std_dev: The standard deviation of the normal distribution for
 338:             factor vectors initialization. Default is ``0.1``.
 339:         lr_all: The learning rate for all parameters. Default is ``0.007``.
 340:         reg_all: The regularization term for all parameters. Default is
 341:             ``0.02``.
 342:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence over
 343:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 344:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence over
 345:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 346:         lr_pu: The learning rate for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence over
 347:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 348:         lr_qi: The learning rate for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence over
 349:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 350:         lr_yj: The learning rate for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence over
 351:             ``lr_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 352:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Takes precedence
 353:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 354:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Takes precedence
 355:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 356:         reg_pu: The regularization term for :math:`p_u`. Takes precedence
 357:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 358:         reg_qi: The regularization term for :math:`q_i`. Takes precedence
 359:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 360:         reg_yj: The regularization term for :math:`y_j`. Takes precedence
 361:             over ``reg_all`` if set. Default is ``None``.
 362:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 363:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 364:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 365:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 366:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 367:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 368:             ``None``.
 369:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 370: 
 371:     Attributes:
 372:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 373:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 374:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 375:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 376:         yj(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The (implicit) item
 377:             factors (only exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 378:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 379:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 380:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 381:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)

 521:     """A collaborative filtering algorithm based on Non-negative Matrix
 522:     Factorization.
 523: 
 524:     This algorithm is very similar to :class:`SVD`. The prediction
 525:     :math:`\\hat{r}_{ui}` is set as:
 526: 
 527:     .. math::
 528:         \hat{r}_{ui} = q_i^Tp_u,
 529: 
 530:     where user and item factors are kept **positive**. Our implementation
 531:     follows that suggested in :cite:`NMF:2014`, which is equivalent to
 532:     :cite:`Zhang96` in its non-regularized form. Both are direct applications
 533:     of NMF for dense matrices :cite:`NMF_algo`.
 534: 
 535:     The optimization procedure is a (regularized) stochastic gradient descent
 536:     with a specific choice of step size that ensures non-negativity of factors,
 537:     provided that their initial values are also positive.
 538: 
 539:     At each step of the SGD procedure, the factors :math:`f` or user :math:`u`
 540:     and item :math:`i` are updated as follows:
 541: 
 542:     .. math::
 543:         p_{uf} &\\leftarrow p_{uf} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if}
 544:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{i \in I_u} q_{if} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 545:         \\lambda_u |I_u| p_{uf}}\\\\
 546:         q_{if} &\\leftarrow q_{if} &\cdot \\frac{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf}
 547:         \\cdot r_{ui}}{\\sum_{u \in U_i} p_{uf} \\cdot \\hat{r_{ui}} +
 548:         \lambda_i |U_i| q_{if}}\\\\
 549: 
 550:     where :math:`\lambda_u` and :math:`\lambda_i` are regularization
 551:     parameters.
 552: 
 553:     This algorithm is highly dependent on initial values. User and item factors
 554:     are uniformly initialized between ``init_low`` and ``init_high``. Change
 555:     them at your own risks!
 556: 
 557:     A biased version is available by setting the ``biased`` parameter to
 558:     ``True``. In this case, the prediction is set as
 559: 
 560:     .. math::
 561:         \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + b_u + b_i + q_i^Tp_u,
 562: 
 563:     still ensuring positive factors. Baselines are optimized in the same way as
 564:     in the :class:`SVD` algorithm. While yielding better accuracy, the biased
 565:     version seems highly prone to overfitting so you may want to reduce the
 566:     number of factors (or increase regularization).
 567: 
 568:     Args:
 569:         n_factors: The number of factors. Default is ``15``.
 570:         n_epochs: The number of iteration of the SGD procedure. Default is
 571:             ``50``.
 572:         biased(bool): Whether to use baselines (or biases). Default is
 573:             ``False``.
 574:         reg_pu: The regularization term for users :math:`\lambda_u`. Default is
 575:             ``0.06``.
 576:         reg_qi: The regularization term for items :math:`\lambda_i`. Default is
 577:             ``0.06``.
 578:         reg_bu: The regularization term for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for
 579:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 580:         reg_bi: The regularization term for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for
 581:             biased version. Default is ``0.02``.
 582:         lr_bu: The learning rate for :math:`b_u`. Only relevant for biased
 583:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 584:         lr_bi: The learning rate for :math:`b_i`. Only relevant for biased
 585:             version. Default is ``0.005``.
 586:         init_low: Lower bound for random initialization of factors. Must be
 587:             greater than ``0`` to ensure non-negative factors. Default is
 588:             ``0``.
 589:         init_high: Higher bound for random initialization of factors. Default
 590:             is ``1``.
 591:         random_state(int, RandomState instance from numpy, or ``None``):
 592:             Determines the RNG that will be used for initialization. If
 593:             int, ``random_state`` will be used as a seed for a new RNG. This is
 594:             useful to get the same initialization over multiple calls to
 595:             ``fit()``.  If RandomState instance, this same instance is used as
 596:             RNG. If ``None``, the current RNG from numpy is used.  Default is
 597:             ``None``.
 598:         verbose: If ``True``, prints the current epoch. Default is ``False``.
 599: 
 600:     Attributes:
 601:         pu(numpy array of size (n_users, n_factors)): The user factors (only
 602:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 603:         qi(numpy array of size (n_items, n_factors)): The item factors (only
 604:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 605:         bu(numpy array of size (n_users)): The user biases (only
 606:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
 607:         bi(numpy array of size (n_items)): The item biases (only
 608:             exists if ``fit()`` has been called)
